Scatterplot Visualizations

Believable Clusters

Let’s take a look at what the scatterplots look like for the more believable structure in the dataset

scatterViz <- function(data,x,y,label=FALSE,label_x=NA,label_y=NA){
  data <- filter(data, oBC_feature_call %in% c(x,y)) %>%
    pivot_wider(id_cols = genes, names_from = oBC_feature_call, values_from = expression)
  
  if(label == F){
     p1 <- ggplot(data, aes_string(x=x, y=y)) +
      geom_point() +
      theme(aspect.ratio = 1)
  }
 
  if(label == T){
    # make column for labels
    data$label <- ifelse(data[[x]] > label_x | data[[x]] < -label_x | data[[y]] > label_y | data[[y]] < -label_y,
                     as.character(data$genes), NA)
    
    p1 <- ggplot(data, aes_string(x=x, y=y)) +
      geom_point() +
      geom_text_repel(aes(label = label)) +
      theme(aspect.ratio = 1)
  } 
  
  return(p1)
}

Cluster 2

We can see that IL1A, IL15, ADIPOQ, and TGFB3 form a small cluster while MIF, TNF, IL9, OSM, and TSLP form a different cluster. There is quite a bit of correlation between these two though.
